posts.name: Rod
posts.cooked: Does anyone know of a zip tie/cable tie tool that actually flush cuts after it pulls them tight?  I picked up a couple off the 'Zon and they leave nasty sharp ends sticking out.  Uncool.

posts.name: Cory Walters
posts.cooked: Seconded, great for making zipties tight and flush. We don’t use them for wire management zipties as they get to tight for that purpose.

posts.name: JCharlton
posts.cooked:
I was lucky enough to find a Thomas & Betts ERG50 cheap second hand. Fantastic tool, can’t recommend it enough.

I was unlucky enough to lose it at a field set-up in Montreal, so if it turns up in a road case in Manchester could someone hold it for me?

posts.name: FrankJ
posts.cooked: Automation Direct sells them . Almost all of them are adjustable to get the tension correct for the zip tie you are using. I would not count on any of them leaving baby smooth cuts.

posts.name: Rod
posts.cooked: The one from AD looks like the one I got off Amazon that left a pretty long and sharp tail…  Have you used that model before?

posts.name: FrankJ
posts.cooked: I have a handful of zip tie guns from different sources. I have at least a couple from AD. They run together so I don’t really remember which is which. My experience is that it is more about the tension adjustment than the gun. Too high tends to stretch the tail leaving a sharp edge.

posts.name: Troy Dietz
posts.cooked:
Afaik it’s inherent to the design. Tried close to a dozen guns and they’ll all get your wrist.

The real zip tie gun is some decent needlenose and hakko CHP-170.

posts.name: Billfred Leverette (he/him/not Bill)
posts.cooked: We just pull by hand and then hit them with flush cutters.  I think ours is McMaster 3621A36 .  Not hard at all to get a zip tie head that’s smoother than a Cadillac on a freshly-paved highway.

posts.name: Rod
posts.cooked:
Another round of zip-tie shootout.  The gold standard is stegg85’s method on the right. image 1401×1031 220 KB Top view of the cuts: image 1414×956 243 KB And the contenders Cheap-O off Amazon, CK 95003 from McMaster, Panduit GS2B, and Ty-Rap ERG50.  The CK is the cheapest that does a solid job.  The Panduits are available on Fleabay for $40-50.  NOTE: the tension is important for function!  If you have the tension set way too low for your zip-tie, you will get a sticking out end even with the Ty-Rap tool!  It really needs to pull, stretch, cut, and allow snap back. image 1421×1017 438 KB Gratuitous detail shot of the working bits of the Panduit.  Note the tiny, sharp, single bevel blade in it.  A little grinding on the end could improve its trimming performance further. image 1070×815 206 KB
